    "body": "I think a step in the right direction would be to take the closest config file no matter whether it is .js or .ts.\r\n\r\nThat would allow having a `./build` folder where a compiled project could function.\r\n\r\nRight now the behavior is:\r\n1. Scan for a .ts config file all the way up in the directory hierarchy, if it is found, use it\r\n2. If no .ts config file is found, look for .js\r\n\r\nThat means that if you have a .ts config file anywhere up in the dir structure, it is preferred over the closer compiled .js config file.\r\n\r\nBetter behavior would be:\r\n1. Start at the CWD\r\n2.  Is there a config file? \r\n * If there is one, use it. \r\n * If there are both .ts  and .js, throw an error\r\n * if there is none look into the parent directory, repeat 2.\r\n",
